T1  - Learning From Disagreement in the U.S. Treasury Bond Market
AU  - GIACOLETTI, MARCO
AU  - LAURSEN, KRISTOFFER T.
AU  - SINGLETON, KENNETH J.
Y1  - 2021/02/01
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/02/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12971
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
JA  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 395
EP  - 441
VL  - 76
IS  - 1
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jofi.12971
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT We study risk premiums in the U.S. Treasury bond market from the perspective of a Bayesian econometrician BLwho learns in real time from disagreement among investors about future bond yields. Notably, disagreement has substantial predictive power for yields, and BL's risk premiums are less volatile than those in the analogous model without learning. BL's forecasts are substantially more accurate than the consensus forecasts of market professionals, particularly following U.S. recessions. The predictive power of disagreement is distinct from the (much weaker) one of inflation and output growth. Rather, it appears to reflect uncertainty about future fiscal policy.
ER  - 

